Each one makes symbolic links to that original, main "!Mods" folder and the folders within it, as well as symbolic links to the individual files such as MC Command Center https://t.co/CiODd2Yg40

So then I did some googling

hey, google, can you make symbolic links with a .bat file? 🤔

Can you do a symbolic link to a single file? 🤔

You see, I don't have my Sims 4 Documents folder in my My Documents folder. I have a symbolic link that TELLS my PC that Sims 4 is in My Documents/Electronic Arts when ACTUALLY it's on E:/The Sims 4 (Documents)/The Sims 4

I fricking LOVE symbolic links
So today I did something a little different...

Then I updated all the mods that needed updating that I could find. I've probably missed a few! That's okay.

Usually what I then do is copy + paste those folders into my current saves. This means I have ACTUAL COPIES of every mod x4+ and all my (200gb) CC x4

this is bad.
So today I tossed all my mods out of all those individual folders and made this singular "all mods folder" which compliments my "all CC, merged" and "all CC, unmerged" folders https://t.co/P0LtBEyvS1

The problem is I don't trust EA to do it this way. So it won't happen.
I just think it could work out really nicely if they did it like that. Especially the way Project Zomboid have done it which is prioritize singleplayer gameplay but incorporate multiplayer in too.
And I guess EA could have their own Official servers 🙄 if they wanted.

Then we could all play in towns for dedicated servers, do roleplay or just chill. Similar to ARK they'd all have their own settings - a MM server with long lifespans, an alpha server with short ones etc.
This would be a bit like ARK where when you join a dedicated ARK server, if you don't have the mods it automatically downloads them so you can play.

Then when you make a sim with CC, it should ask the other players if they want to add that CC to their server folder. You can tick "automatic yes/dont ask" or "automatic no/dont ask" or just answer every time. A CC'd sim without CC will default to vanilla, but have a CC marker.

I think it could work with mods and CC too, similar to those games. For example you could host a dedicated "maxis match, child friendly" server, or a dedicated "alpha, 18+" server for Basemental, Sacrifical etc. Maybe even WW if EA didn't get mad.

I think a #Sims5 multiplayer could be cool IF it was done right. First off, it should absolutely be a singleplayer experience you can invite friends into and have dedicated servers (see: Project Zomboid, Don't Starve Together etc).
